<br>
I will be as clear as possible.  If an enchanter using charm brings 300-500 DPS to a group or raid <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(and 300 DPS has demonstrated to my satisfaction)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, with ordinary risk and support requirements, then enchanters will be chosen as damage dealers in raids and groups to the exclusion of all other classes.<br>
<br>
Are you telling me that this is not imbalanced?<br>
<br>
Why have a rogue, ranger, mage, monk, wizard, etc., when for the same group slot you can have an enchanter doing at least twice the damage, if not three times the damage?<br>
<br>
If only enchanters are chosen to deal damage, what role does that leave classes whose contribution is almost entirely damage, such as rogues, mages, and wizards?<br>
<br>
Are you telling me that I should not be concerned about becoming obsolete?<br>
<br>
Are you suggesting that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Call of the Archmage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> should act as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;pay off,&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to buy my silence while melees become obsolete?<br>
<br>
So far as I can tell, the risk and cost of charming 300-500 DPS mobs is comparable to that of ordinary player tanking, but the reward is vastly more.<br>
<br>
How is this balanced?<br>
